<p><a name="Notes" id="Notes"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Critique_of_Pure_Reason&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="references-small references-column-count references-column-count-2" style="-moz-column-count:2; column-count:2;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> "Aesthetic" here means sensation, and not art theory as it is now used.</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> see Henry Allison, "Kant's Transcendental Idealism"</li>
<li id="cite_note-Critique-2">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Critique_2-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Critique_2-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> Immanuel Kant, Critique of Pure Reason, trans. and ed. by Paul Guyer and Allen W. Wood, Cambridge Univ. Press, 1998, pp. 8-9 (translators' introduction).</li>
</ol>
</div>
